  "response": "To determine the marks and rank needed to get Aerospace Engineering at IIT Bombay in JEE Advanced 2017, we need to look at the cutoff data from that year. Unfortunately, precise marks are not publicly released by IIT Bombay. However, we can determine the approximate rank required.\n\nBased on the data available from various sources (including coaching institutes and analysis of previous years' cutoffs), here's an approximate idea:\n\n*   **General Category:**  To have a good chance, you likely needed a rank within the top 1500-1800. The closing rank for Aerospace Engineering at IIT Bombay was typically around this range in 2017.\n\n*   **OBC-NCL:** The rank required would likely be in the range of 600-700.\n\n*   **SC:** The rank required would likely be in the range of 350-400.\n\n*   **ST:** The rank required would likely be in the range of 150-200.\n\n* **Marks:** Since marks fluctuate from year to year based on the difficulty of the paper, it is challenging to pinpoint the exact marks. However, analyzing past trends, a score in the range of 220-240 (out of 360) likely would have put you in the rank range required for the General category.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **These are approximate figures.** Actual cutoffs can vary slightly depending on the difficulty of the exam, the number of seats available, and the overall performance of the candidates.\n*   **Category Matters:** The rank required varies significantly based on your category (General, OBC-NCL, SC, ST).\n\n**How to get more precise information (though not guaranteed):**\n\n*   **Talk to seniors:** If you know someone who got into IIT Bombay Aerospace in 2017, they might have a better recollection of the approximate marks and ranks.\n*   **Coaching Institute Resources:** Some coaching institutes may have compiled more detailed cutoff analyses from previous years. Check their websites or contact them.\n\n**In summary, while the exact marks are difficult to determine, a rank in